    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p>Not published before <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>132800</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            <p>Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#belzic2022"/>, catalogue <citedRange>B.17</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#_ων"><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><seg part="F">ων</seg></name> 
                        <persName type="attested" key=""><name type="patronymic" nymRef="#Ὑάκινθος">Ὑακίνθ<supplied reason="lost">ω</supplied></name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>ôn fils de Hyakinthos.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>on son of Hyakinthos.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>on figlio di Hyakinthos.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>This base is known only from a transcription in Chamoux's unpublished notebook. The tomb has been carefully explored by S. Farag and J.M. Reynolds in 
               1970. As they do not mention this base, it had probably been moved or broken off between Chamoux's visit in 1947 and their own exploration in 1970.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
